<section class="intro-section">
  <div class="max-w">
    <span class="section-label">Understanding it</span>
    <h2 class="section-title">What erectile dysfunction actually is</h2>
    <p>Erectile dysfunction (ED) is the consistent difficulty getting or keeping an erection firm enough for sex. An occasional off night isn&#8217;t a concern &#8212; it becomes worth discussing when it happens regularly, over weeks or months.</p>
    <p><strong>It is very common.</strong> Most men experience it at some point, and the likelihood increases gradually with age. It is rarely &#8220;just in your head&#8221; &#8212; in most cases there&#8217;s an underlying physical contributor, often one that responds well to treatment once identified.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="factors-section">
  <div class="max-w">
    <div style="margin-bottom:0;">
      <span class="section-label">Common contributors</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">What tends to cause it</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">ED is usually a signal from the body, not an isolated problem. These are the factors doctors check for most often.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="factors-grid">
      <div class="factor-card">
        <div class="factor-icon">&#129505;</div>
        <p class="factor-name">Blood flow &#38; blood vessels</p>
        <p class="factor-desc">High blood pressure, high cholesterol and hardened arteries all restrict the blood flow an erection depends on.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="factor-card">
        <div class="factor-icon">&#128202;</div>
        <p class="factor-name">Diabetes</p>
        <p class="factor-desc">High blood sugar over time can damage both blood vessels and nerves involved in erections.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="factor-card">
        <div class="factor-icon">&#128154;</div>
        <p class="factor-name">Heart health</p>
        <p class="factor-desc">ED can be an early warning sign of cardiovascular disease, sometimes appearing before other symptoms.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="factor-card">
        <div class="factor-icon">&#9879;</div>
        <p class="factor-name">Hormones</p>
        <p class="factor-desc">Low testosterone and thyroid imbalances can both reduce desire and physical response.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="factor-card">
        <div class="factor-icon">&#128083;</div>
        <p class="factor-name">Stress, mood &#38; sleep</p>
        <p class="factor-desc">Anxiety, low mood and poor sleep affect the nervous system signals involved in arousal.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="factor-card">
        <div class="factor-icon">&#128138;</div>
        <p class="factor-name">Lifestyle &#38; medication</p>
        <p class="factor-desc">Smoking, heavy alcohol use, and certain medicines (for blood pressure, mood or other conditions) can all contribute.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

